task.summary: Default task
Started adding WGEM geodatabase parameters.
Adding code at the end of a hot, sticky Thursday.
Initial commit.

Code written. Creates feature class in a separate file GDB. Feature class has CS2007-only fields from LINEARDATA and EVENTDATA (to get the VISIT_STATUS field). Uses an arcpy.da.InsertCursor to add four linear features assigning them VISIT_STATUS values of 1, 2, 3 and <Null>. Resultant feature class will be used to hopefully create web map that can be used in Sweet application to symbolise linear features by VISIT_STATUS.
Added loop to create line features. Also added setting value of LUSE (Them) field. Number of lines created dependent upon number of possible linear LUSE codes (=16).
Modified data_dictionary and wat feature classes and tables are copied.
Committing code before leaving for the day.

Committing code before leaving for the day. Need to re-structure code to select Welsh-nly data from the WGEM schema before appending data into feature classes and related tables. Need to use this approach as SQL subqueries don't work fully in file geodatabases but do in Enterprise (ArcSDE) geodatabases.

Removed redundant/previous code for copying feature classes and related tables.

Updated code to copy feature classes and related tables into separate SDE file geodatabases. Re-structured code to drop non-CS2007 fields from all datasets before appending data into the copied datasets. This is faster then dropping no-CS2007 fields when the copied datasets contain data. Added code to set VISIT_STATUS and REASON_FOR_CHANGE fields to <Null> in SCPTDATA, POINTDATA and EVENTDATA datasets. No need to modify code to add GUIDs to feature classes and related tables.

Version of create-cs2007-wgem-combined-schema.py script to investigate if using an arcpy in_memory workspace allows the script to run faster.

Fixed issue with getting related tables and parent tables from a dictionary. Need to use .copy() to create a copy. In previous code, was using a reference to the dictionary and hence when changing reference it was also changing the dictionary!!!
Changed to creating in_memory feature classes and related tables and when munged write the in_memory feature classes and related tables to SDE specific file geodatabases
Committing before leaving early. Continue on Thursday morning.

Solved issue of not being able to use subqueries with in_memory feature classes or tables. Solved by getting all the unique values for the select field using an arcpy.da.SearchCursor and using these unique values as a where clause in the arcpy.MakeTableView geoprocessing tool.

Script modified to create copies of feature classes and related tables using in_memory workspaces. This significantly reduces the script running time from approx 1 hour to approx ten minutes. Final part of script is to: 1. bring together the different copied feature classes and related tables into one file geodatabase 2. copy necessary domains to the single file geodatabase 3. create relationship classes Then need to check data model using ArcGIS Pro.
